	<head title="CfPBoK paper entry" />
	<body>
		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/paper16</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>Circular Higher-Order Reference Attribute Grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/EmmaSöderberg.html">Emma Söderberg</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_17">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_17</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2014s/paper01.html"><em>Declarative rewriting through circular nonterminal attributes</em></a> (SLE 2014 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The paper advances attribute-grammar technology (higher-order RAGs with circularity/rewrites), i.e., a core meta-language for language implementation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> A central concern is well-defined evaluation in the presence of interacting features (circularity and rewrites), i.e., analysis of language-definition behavior.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It studies how declarative rewrites and circular attributes interact, touching on compositional coordination between specification mechanisms.
</li></ul></li></ul>
